2.10	Yodo-Dono	Yodo-dono	Yodo-dono ) or Yodogimi ) (1569–1615) was a prominently-placed figure in late-Sengoku period. She was a concubine and second wife of Toyotomi Hideyoshi, who was then the most powerful man in Japan. She also became the mother of his son and successor, Hideyori. She was also known as Lady Chacha (茶々). After the death of Hideyoshi, she took the tonsure, becoming a Buddhist nun and taking the name Daikōin (大広院).	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Yodo-dono_cropped.jpg/174px-Yodo-dono_cropped.jpg
